{
  "local_port": 60884,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How is a chemical equation formed?",
  "response": "A chemical equation is a symbolic representation of a chemical reaction. It shows the reactants and products, their quantities, and their states of matter. Here\u2019s a step-by-step process for forming a chemical equation:\n\n1. **Identify the Reactants and Products**: Determine the substances involved in the reaction. The reactants are the starting materials, and the products are the substances formed as a result of the reaction.\n\n2. **Write the Chemical Formulas**: Write the correct chemical formulas for all the reactants and products. Ensure that you know the correct symbols for elements and the formulas for compounds.\n\n3. **Determine the Physical States**: Indicate the physical states of the reactants and products using abbreviations: (s) for solid, (l) for liquid, (g) for gas, and (aq) for aqueous (dissolved in water).\n\n4. **Construct the Skeleton Equation**: Write a preliminary version of the equation, placing reactants on the left side and products on the right side, separated by an arrow (\u2192). \n\n   For example: \\( \\text{A}(s) + \\text{B}(l) \\rightarrow \\text{C}(g) + \\text{D}(aq) \\)\n\n5. **Balance the Equation**: Adjust the coefficients (numbers before the formulas) so that the number of atoms of each element is the same on both sides of the equation. This step ensures that the law of conservation of mass is followed.\n\n   For example: If you have \\( \\text{H}_2 + \\text{O}_2 \\rightarrow \\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\), you'll need to balance it as \\( 2\\text{H}_2 + \\text{O}_2 \\rightarrow 2\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\).\n\n6. **Check Your Work**: Verify that the equation is balanced correctly. Double-check the number of atoms for each element on both sides of the equation.\n\n### Example:\n\nConsider the combustion of methane (CH\u2084):\n\n1. **Identify Reactants and Products**: Methane (CH\u2084) and oxygen (O\u2082) react to form carbon dioxide (CO\u2082) and water (H\u2082O).\n\n2. **Write Chemical Formulas**: CH\u2084, O\u2082, CO\u2082, H\u2082O.\n\n3. **Determine Physical States**: Typically, CH\u2084(g) + O\u2082(g) \u2192 CO\u2082(g) + H\u2082O(l).\n\n4. **Construct Skeleton Equation**: CH\u2084 + O\u2082 \u2192 CO\u2082 + H\u2082O.\n\n5. **Balance the Equation**: Adjust coefficients to balance the atoms:\n   \\( \\text{CH}_4 + 2\\text{O}_2 \\rightarrow \\text{CO}_2 + 2\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\).\n\n6. **Check Your Work**: Verify atoms are balanced:\n   - Carbon: 1 on each side\n   - Hydrogen: 4 on each side\n   - Oxygen: 4 on each side\n\nThe balanced chemical equation is:\n\\( \\text{CH}_4(g) + 2\\text{O}_2(g) \\rightarrow \\text{CO}_2(g) + 2\\text{H}_2\\text{O(l)} \\).",
